<header>
    <h1>A Cup of You: How Coffee in the U.S. Became a Personalized Expression of Identity</h1>
</header>

<div class="content">

    <section class="fade-in-section">
        <div class="section-title">Your Coffee, Your Story</div>
        <p>Coffee has evolved from a morning necessity to a cultural symbol, a deeply personal reflection of identity. Every day, millions of Americans wake up and perform the same ritual: crafting the perfect cup. A splash of oat milk, a shot of vanilla, or a strong espresso, small, deliberate choices that transform a simple beverage into a personal statement.</p>
        <p>Once a utilitarian drink served black or sweetened simply, coffee today is a curated experience, shaped by individual preferences, social values, and cultural trends. It’s not just a beverage, it’s a mirror of identity, reflecting how we see ourselves and how we want to be seen.</p>
        <p>How did this transformation happen? How did coffee become a cultural symbol, a personal ritual, and a shared experience? To explore this, we begin where many coffee stories start: at home.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="fade-in-section">
        <div class="section-title">Coffee at Home: Where Identity Is Crafted</div>
        <p>The ritual of making coffee at home has evolved into a creative act of self-expression. Where once the only choices were cream or sugar, today’s shelves are lined with single-origin beans, oat milks, artisanal syrups, and state-of-the-art brewing gadgets. Home brewing is no longer just about caffeine, it’s about craftsmanship and customization.</p>
        <p>Consider the first visualization: The Equation of Coffee Combinations. Hover over each number to learn more.</p>
        
        <div class="visual fade-in-section">
            <h3>Visual 1: The Equation of Coffee Combinations</h3>
            <div id="observablehq-viewof-coffeeChoicesVisualization-90787eac"></div>
            <p>Credit: <a href="https://observablehq.com/d/d8e20997c14a0cc0@120">Coffee in America; Tommy & Riya by Riya Karumanchi</a></p>
        
            <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@observablehq/inspector@5/dist/inspector.css">
