        <p>This shows how brewing coffee at home has expanded from a binary decision to thousands of combinations, influenced by individual creativity and cultural trends.</p>
        <p>For example:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>In 2010, only 1% of U.S. households owned an espresso machine. By 2020, that number had risen to 9%, as more Americans pursued barista-level precision at home (NCAUSA).</li>
            <li>62% of Americans drink coffee daily, and 66% brew it at home, driven by ritual and preference rather than necessity (NCAUSA).</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Home brewing isn’t just practical, it’s identity creation. Sustainability-conscious drinkers choose fair-trade beans. Minimalists might opt for black coffee. Wellness seekers pick dairy-free milks and natural sweeteners. Each ingredient tells a personal story.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="fade-in-section">
        <p>As we move beyond the home, personal preferences become social markers, shaping shared experiences and cultural signals.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="fade-in-section">
        <div class="section-title">Build Your Brew: Where Taste Becomes Identity</div>
        <p>Coffee preferences aren’t just personal, they’re social markers. Every selection, from the roast to the milk, tells a story of belonging. Consider the second visualization: Build Your Own Coffee. Choose your coffee type, milk, sweetener, and extras, then see how your preferences connect you to others across the country.</p>
        <p>Maybe you prefer cold brew with oat milk and vanilla, placing you among those who choose plant-based milk and popular flavored syrups. Or perhaps you’re a black coffee purist, joining many who forgo sweeteners entirely. If you love espresso with caramel syrup, you align with specialty coffee drinkers who seek bold, crafted experiences.</p>
        <p>These choices are cultural markers shaped by broader trends. Cold brew, once unknown, now accounts for a large share of orders. Espresso pods, once niche, became mainstream after Nespresso’s introduction in 1986. Each selection reflects cultural currents, from wellness movements to nostalgic flavors.</p>
        
        <div class="visual fade-in-section">
            <h3>Visual 2: Interactive Coffee Builder</h3>
            <div id="observablehq-viewof-chart-508e3fac"></div>
            <p>Credit: <a href="https://observablehq.com/d/6a83780530dbae3d@7">Brew Coffee by Riya Karumanchi</a></p>
